# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bird
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The **10th edition of *Systema Naturae*** (Latin; the English title is *A General System of Nature*) is a book written by Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus and published in two volumes in 1758 and 1759, which marks the starting point of zoological nomenclature.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In it, Linnaeus introduced binomial nomenclature for animals, something he had already done for plants in his 1753 publication of *Species Plantarum*.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Before 1758, most biological catalogues had used polynomial names for the taxa included, including earlier editions of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The first work to consistently apply binomial nomenclature across the animal kingdom was the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature therefore chose 1 January 1758 as the "starting point" for zoological nomenclature and asserted that the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae* was to be treated as if published on that date.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Names published before that date are unavailable, even if they would otherwise satisfy the rules.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The only work which takes priority over the 10th edition is Carl Alexander Clerck's **Svenska Spindlar** or **Aranei Suecici**, which was published in 1757, but is also to be treated as if published on January 1, 1758.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] During Linnaeus' lifetime, *Systema Naturae* was under continuous revision.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Progress was incorporated into new and ever-expanding editions; for example, in his 1st edition (1735), whales and manatees were originally classified as species of fish (as was thought to be the case then).
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In the 10th edition, they were both moved into the mammal class.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The animal kingdom, as described by Linnaeus: "Animals enjoy sensation by means of a living organization, animated by a medullary substance; perception by nerves; and motion by the exertion of the will.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They have members for the different purposes of life; organs for their different senses; and faculties (or powers) for the application of their different perceptions.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The list has been broken down into the original six classes Linnaeus described for animals: **Mammalia**, **Aves**, **Amphibia**, **Pisces**, **Insecta**, and **Vermes**.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] By current standards Pisces and Vermes are informal groupings, Insecta also contained arachnids and crustaceans, and one order of Amphibia comprised sharks, lampreys, and sturgeons.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described mammals as: "Animals that suckle their young by means of lactiferous teats.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In external and internal structure they resemble man: most of them are quadrupeds; and with man, their natural enemy, inhabit the surface of the Earth.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described birds as: "A beautiful and cheerful portion of created nature consisting of animals having a body covered with feathers and down; protracted and naked jaws (the beak), two wings formed for flight, and two feet.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described fish as: "Always inhabiting the waters; are swift in their motion and voracious in their appetites.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They breathe by means of gills, which are generally united by a bony arch; swim by means of radiate fins, and are mostly covered over with cartilaginous scales.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described his "Vermes" as: "Animals of slow motion, soft substance, able to increase their bulk and restore parts which have been destroyed, extremely tenacious of life, and the inhabitants of moist places.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Many of them are without a distinct head, and most of them without feet.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They are principally distinguished by their tentacles (or feelers).
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The second volume, published in 1759, detailed the kingdom Plantae, in which Linnaeus included true plants, as well as fungi, algae and lichens.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In addition to repeating the species he had previously listed in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), and those published in the intervening period, Linnaeus described several hundred new plant species.
[src:bird/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The species from *Species Plantarum* were numbered sequentially, while the new species were labelled with letters.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The book was effectively the first "field guide" for non-specialists.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick provides an accurate illustration of each species, from life if possible, or from skins.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The common and scientific name(s) are listed, citing the naming authorities.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The bird is described, with its distribution and behaviour, often with extensive quotations from printed sources or correspondents.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Those who provided skins or information are acknowledged.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The species are grouped into families such as "Of the Falcon", using the limited and conflicting scientific sources of the time.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The families of land birds are further grouped into birds of prey, omnivorous birds, insectivorous birds, and granivorous birds, while the families of water birds are simply listed, with related families side by side.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species entry begins on a new page; any spaces at the ends of entries are filled with tail-pieces, small, often humorous woodcuts of country life.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] *British Birds* remains in print, and has attracted the attention of authors such as Jenny Uglow.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Critics note Bewick's skill as a naturalist as well as an engraver.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The arrangement of the species was by alphabetical order in Gessner's *Historia animalium*, and by arbitrary criteria in most other early works.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The first modern ornithology, intended to describe all the then-known birds worldwide, was produced by Ray and Willughby and published in Latin as *Ornithologiae Libri Tres* (*Three Books of Ornithology*) in 1676, and in English, as *The Ornithology of Francis Willughby of Middleton*, in 1678.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Its innovative features were an effective classification system based on anatomical features, including the bird's beak, feet and overall size, and a dichotomous key, which helped readers to identify birds by guiding them to the page describing that group.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The authors also placed an asterisk against species of which they had no first-hand knowledge, and were therefore unable to verify.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The commercial success of the *Ornithology* is unknown, but it was historically significant, influencing writers including René Réaumur, Mathurin Jacques Brisson, Georges Cuvier and Carl Linnaeus in compiling their own works.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] George Edwards was a leading British naturalist and illustrator in the 17th century.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] He was the librarian to the Royal College of Physicians with access to their collection of 8,000 books, and he used these, together with stuffed and live animals, to produce illustrated publications.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] His four-volume *A Natural History of Uncommon Birds* (1743–1751) and its three supplements covered more than 600 natural history topics, and his publications enabled Linnaeus to name 350 bird species, including many type specimens.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] When he was researching published sources for his bird project, Bewick relied particularly on Edwards' book and the multi-volume *Histoire Naturelle* of the French naturalist Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Thomas Bewick was born at Cherryburn, a house in the parish of Mickley, Northumberland, and he was apprenticed at the age of 14 to Ralph Beilby, an engraver in Newcastle upon Tyne, and learnt how to engrave on wood and metal.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The business prospered, becoming Newcastle's leading engraving service with an enviable reputation for high-quality work and good service.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Now partners, Bielby and Bewick published their *History of Quadrupeds* in 1790, and its success encouraged them to consider producing a new book on British birds.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] In preparation for this major work, Bewick spent several years engraving the necessary wood blocks.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick became well known for his engravings, including the woodcuts for Oliver Goldsmith's *Traveller* and *The Deserted Village*, for Thomas Parnell's *Hermit*, and for William Somervile's *Chase*.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Perhaps the best known of his prints is *The Chillingham Bull*, executed on an exceptionally large woodblock for Marmaduke Tunstall, a Yorkshire landowner.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick also produced and illustrated several editions of Aesop's Fables throughout his creative life.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] His success meant that Bewick had at least 30 pupils who worked for him and Beilby as apprentices, the first of whom was his younger brother John.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick died at his home on 8 November 1828.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] He was buried in Ovingham churchyard, beside his late wife Isabella, who had died two years earlier on 1 February 1826, and not far from his parents and his brother John.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The preface to *A History of British Birds* states that "while one of the editors [Bewick] of this work was engaged in preparing the cuts, which are faithfully drawn from Nature, and engraved upon wood, the compilation of the descriptions ..
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] What the preface does not say is the reason for this statement about the "editors", which was an angry stand-off between Bewick and Beilby.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Beilby's original intention was to have an introduction which merely thanked Bewick for his "assistance", and a title-page naming Beilby as the sole author.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's friend (and his wife's godfather) Thomas Hornby heard of this, and informed Bewick.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] An informal trade panel met to judge the matter, and the preface as printed was the result; Beilby's name did not appear on the title-page.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species of bird is presented in a few pages (generally between two and four; occasionally, as with the mallard or "Common Wild Duck", a few more).
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The first item is a woodcut print of the bird, always either perched or standing on the ground, even in the case of water birds – such as the smew – that (as winter visitors) do not nest in Britain, and consequently are rarely seen away from water there.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then presents the name, with variations, and the Latin and French equivalents.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, "The Musk Duck" is also named on the line below as "Cairo, Guinea, or Indian Duck", and the next line "(*Anas moschata*, Linn.—*Le Canard Musque*, Buff.)" provides the scholarly references to the giving of the Latin binomial by Linnaeus (Linn) and a French description by Buffon (Buff).
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The text begins by stating the size of the bird.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then describes the bird, typically in one paragraph, naming any notable features such as the colour of the eyes ("irides"), the bill, the legs, and plumage on each part of the body.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Next, the origin and distribution of the species are discussed, with notes or quotations from authorities such as John Ray, Gilbert White and Buffon.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then mentions any other facts of interest about the bird; in the case of the musk duck, this concerns its "musky smell, which arises from the liquor secreted in the glands on the rump".
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] If the bird hybridizes with other species, this is described, along with whether the hybrids are fertile ("productive").
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Finally, Bewick acknowledges anyone who had helped him.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The musk duck is stated to have been drawn from a "living specimen" which was however "excepting the head, entirely white", unlike the "general appearance" shown in the woodcut; the bird "was lent to this work by William Losh, Esq., of Point Pleasant, near Newcastle".
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Losh, one of Bewick's many collaborators, was a wealthy partner in Losh, Wilson and Bell, manufacturers of chemicals and iron.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Many of the birds, especially the rarer species, were necessarily illustrated from skins rather than from life.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, for the Sabine's snipe, "The author was favoured by N.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The grouping of species gave Bewick difficulty, as the scientific sources of the time did not agree on how to arrange the species in families, or on a sequence or grouping of those families.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick, for example, uses family groups like "Of the Falcon", in which he includes buzzards and sparrowhawks as well as what are now called falcons.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Each account is closed with a miniature woodcut known from its position in the text as a tail-piece.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] These small artworks depict aspects of country life, often with humorous subjects, but all with Bewick's eye for detail, style, and precision.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Some add to the illustration of the bird in question, as for example the heron, where the tail-piece shows one heron catching an eel, and another flying away.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The tail-piece for Sabine's snipe, a gamebird, shows a hunter firing, and a small bird falling to the ground.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] There is no exclusion of human life from the images: one tail-piece depicts a works complete with smoking chimney beside a river.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The first volume "containing the History and Description of Land Birds" begins with a preface, an introduction, and a list of technical terms illustrated with Bewick's woodcuts.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The birds are divided into granivorous (grain eating) and carnivorous groups, which are explained in some detail.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The speed, senses, flight, migration, pairing behaviour and feeding of birds are then discussed, with observations from Spallanzani and Gilbert White, whose *Natural History and Antiquities of Selborne* was published in 1789.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The second volume "containing the History and Description of Water Birds" begins with its own preface, and its own introduction.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick discusses the question of where many seabirds go to breed, revisits the subject of migration, and concludes with reflections on "an all-wise Providence" as shown in Nature.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The 'foreign birds' are not grouped but just listed directly as species, from Bearded Vulture to Mino.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Fifteen birds are included, with no description, and despite their placement in the table of contents, they appear at the front of the volume as an 'Appendix'.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's *Birds* was an immediate best-seller.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] When *Land Birds* appeared, the whole print sold out by the middle of 1798; 1000 copies of the demy size (8+3⁄4 in × 5+5⁄8 in, 220 mm × 140 mm), 850 of the royal octavo (10 in × 6+1⁄4 in, 250 mm × 160 mm), and 24 of the grand imperial (22 in × 30 in, 560 mm × 760 mm).
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The 1829 *Magazine of Natural History* commented that "Montagu's *Ornithological Dictionary* and Bewick's *Birds* .. have rendered [the] department of natural history popular throughout the land".
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The Tate Gallery writes that Bewick's " best illustrations ... are in his natural history books.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Dissenting from the general tone of praise for Bewick, Jacob Kainen cites claims that "many of the best tailpieces in the *History of British birds* were drawn by Robert Johnson", and that "the greater number of those contained in the second volume were engraved by Clennell.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] To Bewick, nature was the source of joy, challenge and perpetual consolation.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Hilary Spurling, reviewing Uglow's biography of Bewick in *The Observer*, writes that when *Birds* appeared, people all over Britain "became his pupils".
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Spurling cites Charles Kingsley's story of his father's hunting friends from the New Forest mocking him for buying "a book 'about dicky-birds", until, astonished, they saw the book and discovered "things they had known all their lives and never even noticed".
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The *History* is repeatedly mentioned in Charlotte Brontë's 1847 novel *Jane Eyre*.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] John Reed throws the *History of British Birds* at Jane when she is ten; Jane uses the book as a place to which to escape, away from the painful Reed household; and Jane also bases her artwork on Bewick's illustrations.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Jane and Mr Rochester use bird names for each other, including linnet, dove, skylark, eagle, and falcon.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Peter Hall's 1974 film *Akenfield* (from the 1969 book by Ronald Blythe) contains a scene where the grandfather as a young man is reaping a cornfield.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] He weeps when he accidentally crushes a bird's egg, an image derived from Bewick's tail-piece woodcut for the partridge.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The woodcut shows a reaper with a scythe, a dead bird and its nest of a dozen eggs on the ground under the scythe, which has just lifted.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] George Ewart Evans used the image on the title-page of his 1956 book about Blaxhall (near Charsfield, on which 'Akenfield' is probably partly based).
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's reputation as a wood engraver was at its height in the nineteenth century, with the critic John Ruskin writing that the way Bewick had engraved the feathers of his birds was "the most masterly thing ever done in woodcutting".
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The advent of mechanical printing techniques from the 1860s led to something of a decline in his importance, but his fame, already nationwide across Britain for his *Birds*, grew during the nineteenth century.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1830, William Yarrell named Bewick's swan in his honour, and Bewick's son Robert engraved the bird for later editions of *British Birds*.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick had met the American naturalist and bird painter John James Audubon in 1827, and had given him a copy of his *Quadrupeds* for his children.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The American returned the compliment by naming a newly-discovered US bird species as Bewick's wren in honour of his friend.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The way in which Bewick had organised the text and illustrations in his *Birds* takes the form of, and sets a precedent for, modern field guides.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Indeed, the French naturalist François Holandre (1753–1830) assembled a field guide using Bewick's woodcuts as early as 1800.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] A selection of tail-pieces from the book, where they have no captions.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 1 first appeared in 1797, and was reprinted several times in 1797, then again in 1798 and 1800.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 2 first appeared in 1804 (price 11.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] The first imprint was "Newcastle : Printed by Sol.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Hodgson, for Beilby & Bewick; London: Sold by them, and G.C. and J.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1821 a new edition appeared with supplements to both volumes and additional figures, with the imprint "Printed by Edward Walker, Pilgrim-Street, for T.
[src:bird/a-history-of-british-birds] Charnley, Newcastle; and Longman and co., London, 1821." The book was reprinted in many subsequent versions with a 6th edition in 1826, another in 1832, an 8th edition in 1847, and a royal octavo 'Memorial Edition' in 1885.
[src:bird/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The **Accipitriformes** (/ækˌsɪpɪtrɪˈfɔːrmiːz/; from Latin **accipiter** 'hawk' and **formes** 'having the form of') are an order of birds that includes most of the diurnal birds of prey, including hawks, eagles, vultures, kites, ospreys and secretary birds, but not falcons or seriemas.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The generally nocturnal owls, also considered birds of prey, are a separate order from the accipitriformes.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] For a long time, the majority view was to include them with the falcons in the Falconiformes, but many authorities now recognize a separate order Accipitriformes.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] A DNA study published in 2008 indicated that falcons are not closely related to the Accipitriformes, being instead more closely related to parrots and passerines.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The British Ornithologists' Union already recognized the Accipitriformes, and has adopted the move of Falconiformes.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The DNA-based proposal and the NACC and IOC classifications include the New World vultures in the Accipitriformes, while the SACC classifies the New World vultures as a separate order, the Cathartiformes.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] When Cathartiformes is considered a separate order, sister to Accipitriformes, Accipitriformes sensu lato is called Accipitrimorphae.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The Accipitriformes are known from the Middle Eocene and typically have a sharply hooked beak with a soft cere housing the nostrils.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] Their wings are long and fairly broad, suitable for soaring flight, with the outer four to six primary feathers emarginated.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] They have strong legs and feet with raptorial claws and opposable hind claws.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] Almost all Accipitriformes are carnivorous, hunting by sight during the day or at twilight.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] They are exceptionally long-lived, and most have low reproductive rates.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The young have a long, very fast-growing fledgling stage, followed by 3–8 weeks of nest care after first flight, and 1 to 3 years as sexually immature adults.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] The sexes have conspicuously different sizes and sometimes a female is more than twice as heavy as her mate.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] This sexual dimorphism is sometimes most extreme in specialized bird-eaters, such as the *Accipiter* hawks.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] Monogamy is the general rule, although an alternative mate is often selected if one dies.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] Accipitriformes, currently with 262 species and 75 genera in 4 extant families and possibly 1 extinct family, is the largest diurnal raptor order.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] DNA sequence analyses suggest that divergences within Accipitriformes began around the Eocene/Oligocene boundary about 34 mya, with the split of the group including genera *Elanus* and *Gampsonyx* from the other Accipitriformes genera.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] For a complete list of species, see list of Accipitriformes species.
[src:bird/accipitriformes] Phylogeny of Accipitriformes sensu stricto based on Nagy, J. & Tökölyi, J.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Focusing the light scattered by objects in a three dimensional environment into a two dimensional collection of individual bright points of light requires the light to be bent.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] To get a good image of these points of light on a defined area requires a precise systematic bending of light called refraction.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The real image formed from millions of these points of light is what animals see using their retinas.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Very even systematic curvature of parts of the cornea and lens produces this systematic bending of light onto the retina.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Due to the nature of optics the focused image on the retina is always inverted relative to the object.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Different animals live in different environments having different refractive indices involving water, air and often both.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The eyes are therefore required to bend light by different amounts leading to different mechanisms of focus being used in different environments.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The air/cornea interface involves a larger difference in refractive index than hydrated structures within the eye.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] As a result, animals living in air have most of the bending of light achieved at the air/cornea interface with the lens being involved in finer focus of the image.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Generally mammals, birds and reptiles living in air vary their eyes' optical power by subtly and precisely changing the shape of the elastic lens using the ciliary body.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The small difference in refractive index between water and the hydrated cornea means fish and amphibians need to bend the light more using the internal structures of the eye.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Therefore, eyes evolved in water have a mechanism involving changing the distance between a rigid rounder more refractive lens and the retina using less uniform muscles rather than subtly changing the shape of the lens itself using circularly arranged muscles.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Varying forms of direct experimental proof outlined in this article show that most non-aquatic vertebrates achieve focus, at least in part, by changing the shapes of their lenses.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] What is less well understood is how the subtle, precise and very quick changes in lens shape are made.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Direct experimental proof of any lens model is necessarily difficult as the vertebrate lens is transparent and only functions well in the living animal.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] When considering vertebrates, aspects of all models may play varying roles in lens focus.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The models can be broadly divided into two camps: those models that stress the importance of external forces acting on a more passively elastic lens and other models that include forces that may be generated by the lens internally.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The model of a shape changing lens of humans was proposed by Thomas Young in a lecture on the 27th Nov 1800.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Others such as Hermann von Helmholtz and Thomas Henry Huxley refined the model in the mid-1800s explaining how the ciliary muscle contracts, rounding the lens to focus near.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The model may be summarized like this: normally the lens is held under tension by its suspending ligaments and capsule being pulled tight by the pressure of the eyeball.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] At short focal distance the ciliary muscle contracts, stretching the ciliary body and relieving some of the tension on the suspensory ligaments, allowing the elastic lens to become more spherical, increasing refractive power.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Changing focus to an object at a greater distance requires a thinner less curved lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This is achieved by relaxing some of the sphincter-like ciliary muscles allowing the ciliarly body to spring back, pulling harder on the lens making it less curved and thinner, so increasing the focal distance.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] There is a problem with the Helmholtz model in that despite mathematical models being tried, none has come close enough to working using only the Helmholtz mechanisms.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In 1992, Ronald Schachar proposed a model for land based vertebrates that was not well received.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The theory allows mathematical modeling to more accurately reflect the way the lens focuses while also taking into account the complexities in the suspensory ligaments and the presence of radial as well as circular muscles in the ciliary body.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In this model the ligaments may pull to varying degrees on the lens at the equator using the radial muscles, while the ligaments offset from the equator to the front and back are relaxed to varying degrees by contracting the circular muscles.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] These multiple actions operating on the elastic lens allows it to change lens shape at the front more subtly.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Not only changing focus, but also correcting for lens aberrations that might otherwise result from the changing shape while better fitting mathematical modeling.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The "catenary" model of lens focus proposed by Coleman demands less tension on the ligaments suspending the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Rather than the lens as a whole being stretched thinner for distance vision and allowed to relax for near focus, contraction of the circular ciliary muscles results in the lens having less hydrostatic pressure against its front.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The lens front can then reform its shape between the suspensory ligaments in a similar way to a slack chain hanging between two poles might change its curve when the poles are moved closer together.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This model requires precise fluid movement of the lens front only rather than trying to change the shape of the lens as a whole.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] While this concept may be involved in the focusing it has been shown by Scheimpflug photography that the rear of the lens also changes shape in the living eye.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] When Thomas Young proposed the changing of the human lens' shape as the mechanism for focal accommodation in 1801, he thought the lens may be a muscle capable of contraction.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This type of model is termed intracapsular accommodation as it relies on activity within the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In a 1911 Nobel lecture Allvar Gullstrand spoke on "How I found the intracapsular mechanism of accommodation" and this aspect of lens focusing continues to be investigated.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Young spent time searching for the nerves that could stimulate the lens to contract without success.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Since that time it has become clear the lens is not a simple muscle stimulated by a nerve so the 1909 Helmholtz model took precedence.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Pre-twentieth century investigators did not have the benefit of many later discoveries and techniques.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Membrane proteins such as aquaporins which allow water to flow into and out of cells are the most abundant membrane protein in the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Connexins which allow electrical coupling of cells are also prevalent.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Electron microscopy and immunofluorescent microscopy show fiber cells to be highly variable in structure and composition.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Magnetic resonance imaging confirms a layering in the lens that may allow for different refractive plans within it.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The refractive index of human lens varies from approximately 1.406 in the central layers down to 1.386 in less dense layers of the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This index gradient enhances the optical power of the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The accompanying micrograph shows wrinkled fibers from a relaxed sheep lens after it is removed from the animal indicating shortening of the lens fibers during near focus accommodation.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The age related changes in the human lens may also be related to changes in the water dynamics in the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The young human eye can change focus from distance (infinity) to as near as 6.5 cm from the eye.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This dramatic change in focal power of the eye of approximately 15 dioptres (the reciprocal of focal length in metres) occurs as a consequence of a reduction in zonular tension induced by ciliary muscle contraction.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This process can occur in as little as 224 ± 30 milliseconds in bright light.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The amplitude of accommodation declines with age.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] By the fifth decade of life the accommodative amplitude can decline so that the near point of the eye is more remote than the reading distance.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] When this occurs the patient is presbyopic.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Note that these effects are most noticeable when the pupil is large; i.e. in dim light.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Accommodation decreases to about 1 dioptre at the age of 70 years.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The dependency of accommodation amplitude on age is graphically summarized by Duane's classical curves.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The amplitude of accommodation is a clinical measurement that describes the maximum potential increase in optical power that an eye can achieve in adjusting its focus.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] It refers to a certain range of object distances for which the retinal image is as sharply focused as possible.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Amplitude of accommodation is measured during routine eye-examination.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The closest that a normal eye can focus is typically about 10 cm for a child or young adult.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Accommodation then decreases gradually with age, effectively finishing just after age fifty.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The average amplitude of accommodation, in diopters, for a patient of a given age was estimated by Hofstetter in 1950 to be 18.5 − (0.30 × patient age in years) with the minimum amplitude of accommodation as 15 − (0.25 × age in years), and the maximum as 25 − (0.40 × age in years).
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] However, Hofstetter's work was based on data from two early surveys which, although widely cited, used methodology with considerable inherent error.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] When humans accommodate to a near object, they also converge their eyes and constrict their pupils.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The combination of these three movements (accommodation, convergence and miosis) is under the control of the Edinger-Westphal nucleus and is referred to as the *near triad*, or accommodation reflex.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] While it is well understood that proper convergence is necessary to prevent diplopia, the functional role of the pupillary constriction remains less clear.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Arguably, it may increase the depth of field by reducing the aperture of the eye, and thus reduce the amount of accommodation needed to bring the image in focus on the retina.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] There is a measurable ratio (Matthiessen's ratio) between how much convergence takes place because of accommodation (AC/A ratio, CA/C ratio).
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Abnormalities with this can lead to binocular vision problems.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] There are many types of accommodation anomalies.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] It can be broadly classified into two, decreased accommodation and increased accommodation.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Decreased accommodation may occur due to physiological (presbyopia), pharmacological (cycloplegia) or pathological.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Excessive accommodation and spasm of accommodation are types of increased accommodation.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Presbyopia, physiological insufficiency of accommodation due to age related changes in lens (decreased elasticity and increased hardness) and ciliary muscle power is the commonest form of accommodative dysfunction.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] It will cause gradual decrease in near vision.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Accommodative insufficiency is the condition where amplitude of accommodation of a person is lesser compared to physiological limits for their age.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Premature sclerosis of lens or ciliary muscle weaknesses due to systemic or local cases may cause accommodative insufficiency.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Accommodative insufficiency is further categorised into different categories.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Ill-sustained accommodation is a condition similar to accommodative insufficiency.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In this, range of accommodation will be normal, but after excessive near work accommodative power will decrease.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In paralysis of accommodation, amplitude of accommodation is either markedly reduced or completely absent (cycloplegia).
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] It may occur due to ciliary muscle paralysis or occulomotor nerve paralysis.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Parasympatholytic drugs like atropine will also cause paralysis of accommodation.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] If there is amplitude of accommodation between the eyes differ 0.5 dioptre or more, it is considered as unequal.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Organic diseases, head trauma or functional amblyopia may be responsible for unequal accommodation.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Accommodative infacility is also known as accommodative inertia.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In this condition there will be difficulty in changing accommodation from one point to other.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] There may be difficulty in adjusting focus from distance from near.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Spasm of accommodation also known as ciliary spasm is a condition of abnormally excessive accommodation which is out of voluntary control of the person.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Vision may be blurred due to induced pseudomyopia.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Accommodative excess occurs when an individual uses more than normal accommodation for performing certain near work.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Modern definitions simply regard it as an inability to relax accommodation readily.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Aquatic animals include some that also thrive in the air so focusing mechanisms vary more than in those that are only land based.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Some whales and seals are able to focus above and below water having two areas of retina with high numbers of rods and cones rather than one as in humans.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] Having two high resolution area of retina presumably allows two axis of vision one for above and one for below water.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In reptiles and birds, the ciliary body which supports the lens via suspensory ligaments (*ligamentum suspensorium*) also touches the lens with a number of pads on its inner surface.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] These pads compress and release the lens to modify its shape while focusing on objects at different distances; the suspensory ligaments usually perform this function in mammals.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] With vision in fish and amphibians, the lens is fixed in shape, and focusing is instead achieved by moving the lens forwards or backwards within the eye using a muscle called the retractor lentus.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In cartilaginous fish, the suspensory ligaments are replaced by a membrane, including a small muscle at the underside of the lens.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] This muscle pulls the lens forward from its relaxed position when focusing on nearby objects.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In teleosts, by contrast, a muscle (*retractor lentis*) projects from a vascular structure in the floor of the eye, called the *falciform process*, and serves to pull the lens backwards from the relaxed position to focus on distant objects.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The muscle is antagonistic to the suspensory ligaments.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] While amphibians move the lens forward, as do cartilaginous fish, the muscles involved are not similar in either type of animal.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In frogs, there are two muscles, one above and one below the lens, while other amphibians have only the lower muscle.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] In the simplest vertebrates, the lampreys and hagfish, the lens is not attached to the outer surface of the eyeball at all.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] There is no aqueous humor in these fish, and the vitreous body simply presses the lens against the surface of the cornea.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] To focus its eyes, a lamprey flattens the cornea using muscles outside of the eye and pushes the lens backwards.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] While not vertebrate, brief mention is made here of the convergent evolution of vertebrate and Molluscan eyes.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The most complex Molluscan eye is the Cephalopod eye which is superficially similar structure and function to a vertebrate eye, including accommodation, while differing in basic ways such as having a two part lens and no cornea.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] The fundamental requirements of optics must be filled by all eyes with lenses using the tissues at their disposal so superficially eyes all tend to look similar.
[src:bird/accommodation-eye] It is the way optical requirements are met using different cell types and structural mechanisms that varies among animals.
[src:bird/achillesaurus] The holotype specimen of *Achillesaurus,* **MACN-PV-RN 1116**, was discovered in 1995 by a team of the Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales “Bernardino Rivadavia” led by Dr.
[src:bird/achillesaurus] It was found in the Paso Córdova Locality, Río Negro Province, northern Patagonia, where the Santonian-aged Bajo de la Carpa Formation outcrops.
[src:bird/achillesaurus] The genus was a relatively large, basal alvarezsaurid, and a contemporary of *Alvarezsaurus*.
[src:bird/achillesaurus] It is only known from MACN-PV-RN 1116, a partial skeleton including a sacral vertebra, four tail vertebrae, part of the left thighbone, shin and foot, and the left ilium.
[src:bird/achillesaurus] Agustín Martinelli and Ezequiel Vera, who described the specimen, performed a phylogenetic analysis and found their new genus to be an alvarezsaurid with an unresolved relationship to *Alvarezsaurus* and more derived alvarezsaurids.
[src:bird/achillesaurus] However, Makovicky, Apesteguía & Gianechini (2012) argued that *Achillesaurus* might actually be a junior synonym of *Alvarezsaurus,* which, according to the authors, "is known from the same formation and from which it [i.e.
[src:bird/actinistia] The name **coelacanth** originates from the Permian genus *Coelacanthus*, which was the first scientifically named genus of coelacanths (in 1839), becoming the type genus of **Coelacanthiformes** as other species were discovered and named.
[src:bird/actinistia] Well-represented in freshwater and marine deposits from as early as the Devonian period (more than 410 million years ago), they were thought to have become extinct in the Late Cretaceous, around 66 million years ago.
[src:bird/actinistia] The first living species, *Latimeria chalumnae*, the West Indian Ocean coelacanth, was described from specimens fished off the coast of South Africa from 1938 onward; they are now also known to inhabit the seas around the Comoro Islands off the east coast of Africa.
[src:bird/actinistia] The second species, *Latimeria menadoensis*, the Indonesian coelacanth, was discovered in the late 1990s, which inhabits the seas of Eastern Indonesia, from Manado to Papua.
[src:bird/actinistia] However, studies of fossil coelacanths have shown that coelacanth body shapes (and their niches) were much more diverse than what was previously thought, and often differed significantly from *Latimeria*.
[src:bird/actinistia] The genus name *Latimeria* commemorates Marjorie Courtenay-Latimer, who discovered the first specimen.
[src:bird/actinistia] The earliest fossils of coelacanths were discovered in the 19th century.
[src:bird/actinistia] Coelacanths were believed to have become extinct at the end of the Cretaceous period.
[src:bird/actinistia] More closely related to tetrapods than to the ray-finned fish, coelacanths were considered a transitional form between fish and tetrapods.
[src:bird/actinistia] On 22 December 1938, the first *Latimeria* specimen was found off the east coast of South Africa, off the Chalumna River (now Tyolomnqa).
[src:bird/actinistia] Museum curator Marjorie Courtenay-Latimer discovered the fish among the catch of a local fisherman.
[src:bird/actinistia] Courtenay-Latimer contacted a Rhodes University ichthyologist, J.
[src:bird/actinistia] Since 1938, West Indian Ocean coelacanth have been found in the Comoros, Kenya, Tanzania, Mozambique, Madagascar, in iSimangaliso Wetland Park, and off the South Coast of Kwazulu-Natal in South Africa.
[src:bird/actinistia] The Comoro Islands specimen was discovered in December 1952.
[src:bird/actinistia] Between 1938 and 1975, 84 specimens were caught and recorded.
[src:bird/actinistia] The second extant species, the Indonesian coelacanth, was first recognized in Manado, North Sulawesi, Indonesia, by Mark V.
[src:bird/actinistia] Erdmann and his wife Arnaz Mehta at a local fish market in September 1997, but were only able to take a few photographs of the first specimen of this species before it was sold.
[src:bird/actinistia] After confirming that it was a unique discovery, Erdmann returned to Sulawesi in November 1997 to interview fishermen and look for further examples.
[src:bird/actinistia] A second specimen was caught by a fisherman in July 1998 and was then handed to Erdmann.
[src:bird/actinistia] The species was described in 1999 by Pouyaud et al. based on Erdmann's 1998 specimen and deposited at a facility of the Indonesian Institute of Sciences (LIPI).
[src:bird/actinistia] During the Paleozoic and Mesozoic, coelacanths had a global distribution, with remains having been found on every continent except Antarctica.
[src:bird/actinistia] The two extant *Latimeria* species, the West Indian Ocean coelacanth and the Indonesian coelacanth, are restricted to the southern and eastern coasts of Africa and northern Indonesia, respectively.
[src:bird/actinistia] Coelacanths are a part of Sarcopterygii or the lobe-finned fishes, the same clade as the lungfish and tetrapods, and they all possess lobed fins as opposed to rayed fins.
[src:bird/actinistia] Externally, several characteristics distinguish coelacanths from other lobe-finned fish: coelacanths have eight fins – two dorsal fins, two pectoral fins, two pelvic fins, one anal fin and one caudal fin.
[src:bird/actinistia] The tail is very nearly equally proportioned and is split by a terminal tuft of fin rays that make up its caudal lobe; this is alternatively termed a trilobate fin (three-lobed) or a diphycercal tail.
[src:bird/actinistia] A secondary tail extending past the primary tail separates the upper and lower halves of the coelacanth.
[src:bird/actinistia] The pectoral fins of coelacanths are lobed and relatively elongate.
[src:bird/actinistia] There are two separate jointed points of articulation between each half of the skull and lower jaws, with the joints being between the quadrate on the skull and articular on the lower jaw and likewise between the symplectic and retroarticular.
[src:bird/actinistia] The dentary bone on the lower jaw is short, and is curved in members of Latimerioidei including living coelacanths.
[src:bird/actinistia] The angular bone on the lower jaw is large.
[src:bird/actinistia] The shoulder girdle is loose from the skull and has an extracleithrum.
[src:bird/actinistia] The front dorsal fin lacks radial bones and is generally sail-like in shape.
[src:bird/actinistia] The anal fin and the posterior dorsal fin are essentially identical and similar in morphology to the paired fins.
[src:bird/actinistia] The scales of coelacanths are generally circular and overlapping, and lack ganoine or cosmine.
[src:bird/actinistia] These scales are either ornamented with denticles, tubercles or ridges capped with enamel.
[src:bird/actinistia] Coelacanths also retain an oil-filled notochord, a hollow, pressurized tube which is replaced by a vertebral column early in embryonic development in most other vertebrates.
[src:bird/actinistia] Most fossil coelacanths have a lung surrounded by a heavily calcified casing.
[src:bird/actinistia] Coelacanths are members of the class Actinistia, with many researchers considering the term "coelacanth" to cover all members of Actinistia.
[src:bird/actinistia] The order Coelacanthiformes has been used for a subgroup of actinistians, containing the modern coelacanths, as well as other extinct closely related actinistians spanning from the Permian onwards.
[src:bird/actinistia] Based on the fossil record, the divergence of coelacanths, lungfish, and tetrapods is thought to have occurred during the Silurian.
[src:bird/actinistia] Over 100 fossil species of coelacanth have been described.
[src:bird/actinistia] The oldest identified coelacanth fossils are around 420–410 million years old, dating to the Pragian stage of the early Devonian.
[src:bird/actinistia] These include *Eoactinistia* from Australia, known only from a fragmentary jaw, as well as *Euporosteus yunnanensis* from China, known from a partial skull that indicates it to be the earliest anatomically modern coelacanth.
[src:bird/actinistia] Some authors have also suggested that the slightly older onychodont *Styloichthys* may also be an early coelacanth.
[src:bird/actinistia] Coelacanths were never a diverse group in comparison to other groups of fish, and reached a peak diversity during the Early Triassic (252–247 million years ago), coinciding with a burst of diversification between the Late Permian and Middle Triassic.
[src:bird/actinistia] Most Mesozoic coelacanths belong to the suborder Latimerioidei, which contains two major subdivisions, the marine Latimeriidae, which contains modern coelacanths, as well as the extinct Mawsoniidae, which were native to brackish, freshwater as well as marine environments.
[src:bird/actinistia] Paleozoic coelacanths are generally small (~30–40 cm or 12–16 in in length), while Mesozoic forms were larger.
[src:bird/actinistia] Several specimens belonging to the Jurassic and Cretaceous mawsoniid coelacanth genera *Trachymetopon* and *Mawsonia* likely reached or exceeded 5 metres (16 feet) in length, making them amongst the largest known fishes of the Mesozoic, and amongst the largest bony fishes of all time.
[src:bird/actinistia] Living coelacanths have been considered "living fossils" based on their supposedly conservative morphology relative to fossil species; however, recent studies have expressed the view that coelacanth morphologic conservatism is a belief not based on data.
[src:bird/actinistia] Fossils suggest that coelacanths were most morphologically diverse during the Devonian and Carboniferous, while Mesozoic species are generally morphologically similar to each other.
[src:bird/actinistia] Cladogram showing the relationships of coelacanth genera after Torino, Soto and Perea, 2021.
[src:bird/actinistia] Living *Latimeria* coelacanths are nocturnal piscivorous drift-hunters, often drifting in a state of near motionlessness.
[src:bird/actinistia] Species of *Latimeria* are opportunistic feeders, hunting cuttlefish, squid, snipe eels, small sharks, and other fish found in their deep reef and volcanic slope habitats.
[src:bird/actinistia] *Latimeria* are also known to swim head down, backwards or belly up to locate their prey,.
[src:bird/actinistia] To move around, they most commonly take advantage of up- or down-wellings of current and drift.
[src:bird/actinistia] Their paired fins stabilize movement through the water.
[src:bird/actinistia] While on the ocean floor, they do not use the paired fins for any kind of movement.
[src:bird/actinistia] *Latimeria* generate thrust with their caudal fins for quick starts.
[src:bird/actinistia] Due to the abundance of its fins, *Latimeria* has high maneuverability and can orient its body in almost any direction in the water.
[src:bird/actinistia] *Latimeria* have been seen doing headstands as well as swimming belly up.
[src:bird/actinistia] It is thought that the rostral organ helps give *Latimeria* electroreception.
[src:bird/actinistia] The electroreceptive rostral organ of living coelacanths is suggested to be primarily used to detect the position of the prey when it is within the vicinity of the mouth just prior to the final strike, rather than for long distance prey detection.
[src:bird/actinistia] Thrust is primarily generated by the fins.
[src:bird/actinistia] The paired fins are very mobile and can be moved in ways unusual among fish fins in order to accomplish precise movements, such as a figure of eight pattern.
[src:bird/actinistia] The generally rounded, broad tail (caudal) fins of most coelacanths including *Latimeria* suggests an adaptation to generally slow swimming with the ability to suddenly accelerate for short speed bursts.
[src:bird/actinistia] Considerable diversity in fossil coelacanth body shape suggests that not all coelacanths had the same life habits as living *Latimeria*.
[src:bird/actinistia] For example the unusual large forked tail of the Early Triassic *Rebellatrix* suggests an adaptation to fast swimming similar to tuna, suggesting that it was a cruising predator, with its tapered asymmetrical other fins likely being used for fine control.
[src:bird/actinistia] A study of the ecology of 5 contemporaneous coelacanth species from the Lower Carboniferous Bear Gulch Limestone, found that they likely exhibited differing life habits indicating niche partitioning.
[src:bird/actinistia] It is suggested that coelacanths living and extinct utilize(d) suction feeding to capture prey, and that this trait had evolved early in their evolutionary history, by the end of the Devonian.
[src:bird/actinistia] Stomach contents of the mawsoniid *Axelrodichthys* from the Early Cretaceous of Brazil suggests that it consumed fish, swallowing its prey whole, as its teeth were too small to effectively break it up in the mouth.
[src:bird/actinistia] Living *Latimeria* coelacanths are ovoviviparous, meaning that the female retains the fertilized eggs within her body while the embryos develop during a gestation period of five years.
[src:bird/actinistia] Typically, females are larger than the males; their scales and the skin folds around the cloaca differ.
[src:bird/actinistia] The male coelacanth has no distinct copulatory organs, just a cloaca, which has a urogenital papilla surrounded by erectile caruncles.
[src:bird/actinistia] It is hypothesized that the cloaca everts to serve as a copulatory organ.
[src:bird/actinistia] Living coelacanth eggs are large, with only a thin layer of membrane to protect them.
[src:bird/actinistia] Embryos hatch within the female and eventually are born alive, which is a rarity in fish.
[src:bird/actinistia] This was only discovered when the American Museum of Natural History dissected its first coelacanth specimen in 1975 and found it pregnant with five embryos.
[src:bird/actinistia] Young coelacanths resemble the adult, the main differences being an external yolk sac, larger eyes relative to body size and a more pronounced downward slope of the body.
[src:bird/actinistia] The juvenile coelacanth's broad yolk sac hangs below the pelvic fins.
[src:bird/actinistia] The scales and fins of the juvenile are completely matured; however, it does lack odontodes, which it gains during maturation.
[src:bird/actinistia] Female *Latimeria* coelacanths give birth to live young, called "pups", in groups of between five and 25 fry at a time; the pups are capable of surviving on their own immediately after birth.
[src:bird/actinistia] Their reproductive behaviors are not well known, but it is believed that they are not sexually mature until after 20 years of age.
[src:bird/actinistia] It was thought that gestation time was 13 to 15 months, though research carried out in 2021 now suggests a gestation period of up to five years, which is 1.5 years longer than the deep-sea frilled shark, the previous record holder.
[src:bird/actinistia] Their scales themselves secrete mucus, which combined with the excessive oil their bodies produce, make coelacanths a slimy food.
[src:bird/actinistia] Where the coelacanth is more common, local fishermen avoid it because of its potential to sicken consumers.
[src:bird/actinistia] As a result, living coelacanths have no real commercial value apart from being coveted by museums and private collectors.
[src:bird/actinistia] Because of their remote deep sea habitat, the conservation status of living coelacanths is difficult to characterize.
[src:bird/actinistia] The IUCN currently classifies *L. chalumnae* as "critically endangered".
[src:bird/actinistia] *L. menadoensis* is considered Vulnerable.
[src:bird/actinistia] The major threat towards the coelacanth is the accidental capture by fishing operations (bycatch), especially commercial deep-sea trawling.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds evolved from earlier theropods, and thus constitute the only known living dinosaurs.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Whilst traditional Linnaean taxonomy placed birds in their own class (owing to their unique morphology and being the only group of animals other than mammals where all its species are warm-blooded), birds are considered reptiles in the modern cladistic sense of the term.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Their closest living relatives are the crocodilians, both forming a clade known as archosaurs.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds are descendants of the primitive avialans (whose members include *Archaeopteryx*) which first appeared during the Late Jurassic.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many social species preserve knowledge across generations (culture).
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds are social, communicating with visual signals, calls, and songs, and participating in such behaviour as cooperative breeding and hunting, flocking, and mobbing of predators.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The vast majority of bird species are socially (but not necessarily sexually) monogamous, usually for one breeding season at a time, sometimes for years, and rarely for life.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Other species have breeding systems that are polygynous (one male with many females) or, rarely, polyandrous (one female with many males).
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds produce offspring by laying eggs which are fertilised through sexual reproduction.
[src:bird/bird-p01] They are usually laid in a nest and incubated by the parents.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most birds have an extended period of parental care after hatching.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many species of birds are economically important as food for human consumption and raw material in manufacturing, with domesticated and undomesticated birds being important sources of eggs, meat, and feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Songbirds, parrots, and other species are popular as pets.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Guano (bird excrement) is harvested for use as a fertiliser.
[src:bird/bird-p01] About 120 to 130 species have become extinct due to human activity since the 17th century, and hundreds more before then.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Human activity threatens about 1,200 bird species with extinction, though efforts are underway to protect them.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Recreational birdwatching is an important part of the ecotourism industry.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The first classification of birds was developed by Francis Willughby and John Ray in their 1676 volume *Ornithologiae*.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Carl Linnaeus modified that work in 1758 to devise the taxonomic classification system currently in use.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds are usually categorised as a biological class in traditional evolutionary taxonomy.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Modern phylogenetic taxonomy places Aves in the clade Theropoda, sometimes with a Linnean rank lower than class, such as subclass or infraclass.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Aves and a sister group, the order Crocodilia, contain the only living representatives of the reptile clade Archosauria.
[src:bird/bird-p01] During the late 1990s, Aves was most commonly defined phylogenetically as all descendants of the most recent common ancestor of modern birds and *Archaeopteryx lithographica*.
[src:bird/bird-p01] However, an earlier definition proposed by Jacques Gauthier gained wide currency in the 21st century, and is used by many scientists including adherents to the *PhyloCode*.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Gauthier defined Aves to include only the crown group of the set of modern birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This was done by excluding most groups known only from fossils, and assigning them, instead, to the broader group Avialae, on the principle that a clade based on extant species should be limited to those extant species and their closest extinct relatives.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Gauthier and de Queiroz identified four different definitions for the same biological name "Aves", which is a problem.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The authors proposed to reserve the term Aves only for the crown group consisting of the last common ancestor of all living birds and all of its descendants, which corresponds to meaning number 4 below.
[src:bird/bird-p01] They assigned other names to the other groups.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Under the fourth definition *Archaeopteryx*, traditionally considered one of the earliest members of Aves, is removed from this group, becoming a non-avian dinosaur instead.
[src:bird/bird-p01] These proposals have been adopted by many researchers in the field of palaeontology and bird evolution, though the exact definitions applied have been inconsistent.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Avialae, initially proposed to replace the traditional fossil content of Aves, is often used synonymously with the vernacular term "bird" by these researchers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most researchers define Avialae as branch-based clade, though definitions vary.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many authors have used a definition similar to "all theropods closer to birds than to *Deinonychus*", with *Troodon* being sometimes added as a second external specifier in case it is closer to birds than to *Deinonychus*.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Avialae is also occasionally defined as an apomorphy-based clade (that is, one based on physical characteristics).
[src:bird/bird-p01] Jacques Gauthier, who named Avialae in 1986, re-defined it in 2001 as all dinosaurs that possessed feathered wings used in flapping flight, and the birds that descended from them.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Despite being currently one of the most widely used, the crown-group definition of Aves has been criticised by some researchers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Their alternative definition is synonymous to Avifilopluma.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Based on fossil and biological evidence, most scientists accept that birds are a specialised subgroup of theropod dinosaurs and, more specifically, members of Maniraptora, a group of theropods which includes dromaeosaurids and oviraptorosaurs, among others.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As scientists have discovered more theropods closely related to birds, the previously clear distinction between non-birds and birds has become blurred.
[src:bird/bird-p01] By the 2000s, discoveries in the Liaoning Province of northeast China, which demonstrated many small theropod feathered dinosaurs, contributed to this ambiguity.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The consensus view in contemporary palaeontology is that the flying theropods, or avialans, are the closest relatives of the deinonychosaurs, which include dromaeosaurids and troodontids.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Together, these form a group called Paraves.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Some basal members of Deinonychosauria, such as *Microraptor*, have features which may have enabled them to glide or fly.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The most basal deinonychosaurs were very small.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This evidence raises the possibility that the ancestor of all paravians may have been arboreal, have been able to glide, or both.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Unlike *Archaeopteryx* and the non-avialan feathered dinosaurs, who primarily ate meat, studies suggest that the first avialans were omnivores.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The Late Jurassic *Archaeopteryx* is well known as one of the first transitional fossils to be found, and it provided support for the theory of evolution in the late 19th century.
[src:bird/bird-p01] *Archaeopteryx* was the first fossil to display both clearly traditional reptilian characteristics—teeth, clawed fingers, and a long, lizard-like tail—as well as wings with flight feathers similar to those of modern birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] It is not considered a direct ancestor of birds, though it is possibly closely related to the true ancestor.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Over 40% of key traits found in modern birds evolved during the 60 million year transition from the earliest bird-line archosaurs to the first maniraptoromorphs, i.e. the first dinosaurs closer to living birds than to *Tyrannosaurus rex*.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The loss of osteoderms otherwise common in archosaurs and acquisition of primitive feathers might have occurred early during this phase.
[src:bird/bird-p01] After the appearance of Maniraptoromorpha, the next 40 million years marked a continuous reduction of body size and the accumulation of neotenic (juvenile-like) characteristics.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Hypercarnivory became increasingly less common while braincases enlarged and forelimbs became longer.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The integument evolved into complex, pennaceous feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The oldest known paravian (and probably the earliest avialan) fossils come from the Tiaojishan Formation of China, which has been dated to the late Jurassic period (Oxfordian stage), about 160 million years ago.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The avialan species from this time period include *Anchiornis huxleyi*, *Xiaotingia zhengi*, and *Aurornis xui*.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The well-known probable early avialan, *Archaeopteryx*, dates from slightly later Jurassic rocks (about 155 million years old) from Germany.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many of these early avialans shared unusual anatomical features that may be ancestral to modern birds but were later lost during bird evolution.
[src:bird/bird-p01] These features include enlarged claws on the second toe which may have been held clear of the ground in life, and long feathers or "hind wings" covering the hind limbs and feet, which may have been used in aerial maneuvering.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Avialans diversified into a wide variety of forms during the Cretaceous period.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many groups retained primitive characteristics, such as clawed wings and teeth, though the latter were lost independently in a number of avialan groups, including modern birds (Aves).
[src:bird/bird-p01] Increasingly stiff tails (especially the outermost half) can be seen in the evolution of maniraptoromorphs, and this process culminated in the appearance of the pygostyle, an ossification of fused tail vertebrae.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In the late Cretaceous, about 100 million years ago, the ancestors of all modern birds evolved a more open pelvis, allowing them to lay larger eggs compared to body size.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Around 95 million years ago, they evolved a better sense of smell.
[src:bird/bird-p01] A third stage of bird evolution starting with Ornithothoraces (the "bird-chested" avialans) can be associated with the refining of aerodynamics and flight capabilities, and the loss or co-ossification of several skeletal features.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Particularly significant are the development of an enlarged, keeled sternum and the alula, and the loss of grasping hands.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The first large, diverse lineage of short-tailed avialans to evolve were the Enantiornithes, or "opposite birds", so named because the construction of their shoulder bones was in reverse to that of modern birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Enantiornithes occupied a wide array of ecological niches, from sand-probing shorebirds and fish-eaters to tree-dwelling forms and seed-eaters.
[src:bird/bird-p01] While they were the dominant group of avialans during the Cretaceous period, Enantiornithes became extinct along with many other dinosaur groups at the end of the Mesozoic era.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many species of the second major avialan lineage to diversify, the Euornithes (meaning "true birds", because they include the ancestors of modern birds), were semi-aquatic and specialised in eating fish and other small aquatic organisms.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Unlike the Enantiornithes, which dominated land-based and arboreal habitats, most early euornithians lacked perching adaptations and likely included shorebird-like species, waders, and swimming and diving species.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The latter included the superficially gull-like *Ichthyornis* and the Hesperornithiformes, which became so well adapted to hunting fish in marine environments that they lost the ability to fly and became primarily aquatic.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The early euornithians also saw the development of many traits associated with modern birds, like strongly keeled breastbones, toothless, beaked portions of their jaws (though most non-avian euornithians retained teeth in other parts of the jaws).
[src:bird/bird-p01] Euornithes also included the first avialans to develop true pygostyle and a fully mobile fan of tail feathers, which may have replaced the "hind wing" as the primary mode of aerial maneuverability and braking in flight.
[src:bird/bird-p01] A study on mosaic evolution in the avian skull found that the last common ancestor of all Neornithes might have had a beak similar to that of the modern hook-billed vanga and a skull similar to that of the Eurasian golden oriole.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As both species are small aerial and canopy foraging omnivores, a similar ecological niche was inferred for this hypothetical ancestor.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most studies agree on a Cretaceous age for the most recent common ancestor of modern birds but estimates range from the Early Cretaceous to the latest Cretaceous.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Similarly, there is no agreement on whether most of the early diversification of modern birds occurred in the Cretaceous and associated with breakup of the supercontinent Gondwana or occurred later and potentially as a consequence of the Cretaceous–Palaeogene extinction event.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This disagreement is in part caused by a divergence in the evidence; most molecular dating studies suggests a Cretaceous evolutionary radiation, while fossil evidence points to a Cenozoic radiation (the so-called 'rocks' versus 'clocks' controversy).
[src:bird/bird-p01] The discovery in 2005 of *Vegavis* from the Maastrichtian, the last stage of the Late Cretaceous, proved that the diversification of modern birds started before the Cenozoic era.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The affinities of an earlier fossil, the possible galliform *Austinornis lentus*, dated to about 85 million years ago, are still too controversial to provide a fossil evidence of modern bird diversification.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In 2020, *Asteriornis* from the Maastrichtian was described, it appears to be a close relative of Galloanserae, the earliest diverging lineage within Neognathae.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Attempts to reconcile molecular and fossil evidence using genomic-scale DNA data and comprehensive fossil information have not resolved the controversy.
[src:bird/bird-p01] However, a 2015 estimate that used a new method for calibrating molecular clocks confirmed that while modern birds originated early in the Late Cretaceous, likely in Western Gondwana, a pulse of diversification in all major groups occurred around the Cretaceous–Palaeogene extinction event.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Modern birds would have expanded from West Gondwana through two routes.
[src:bird/bird-p01] One route was an Antarctic interchange in the Paleogene.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The other route was probably via Paleocene land bridges between South America and North America, which allowed for the rapid expansion and diversification of Neornithes into the Holarctic and Paleotropics.
[src:bird/bird-p01] On the other hand, the occurrence of *Asteriornis* in the Northern Hemisphere suggest that Neornithes dispersed out of East Gondwana before the Paleocene.
[src:bird/bird-p01] All modern birds lie within the crown group Aves (alternately Neornithes), which has two subdivisions: the Palaeognathae, which includes the flightless ratites (such as the ostriches) and the weak-flying tinamous, and the extremely diverse Neognathae, containing all other birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] These two subdivisions have variously been given the rank of superorder, cohort, or infraclass.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The number of known living bird species is around 11,000 although sources may differ in their precise numbers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Cladogram of modern bird relationships based on Stiller *et al* (2024)., showing the 44 orders recognised by the IOC.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The classification of birds is a contentious issue.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Sibley and Ahlquist's *Phylogeny and Classification of Birds* (1990) is a landmark work on the subject.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most evidence seems to suggest the assignment of orders is accurate, but scientists disagree about the relationships among the orders themselves; evidence from modern bird anatomy, fossils and DNA have all been brought to bear on the problem, but no strong consensus has emerged.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Fossil and molecular evidence from the 2010s is providing an increasingly clear picture of the evolution of modern bird orders.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In 2010, the genome had been sequenced for only two birds, the chicken and the zebra finch.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As of 2022, the genomes of 542 species of birds had been completed.
[src:bird/bird-p01] At least one genome has been sequenced from every order.
[src:bird/bird-p01] These include at least one species in about 90% of extant avian families (218 out of 236 families recognised by the *Howard and Moore Checklist*).
[src:bird/bird-p01] Being able to sequence and compare whole genomes gives researchers many types of information, about genes, the DNA that regulates the genes, and their evolutionary history.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This has led to reconsideration of some of the classifications that were based solely on the identification of protein-coding genes.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Waterbirds such as pelicans and flamingos, for example, may have in common specific adaptations suited to their environment that were developed independently.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds live and breed in most terrestrial habitats and on all seven continents, reaching their southern extreme in the snow petrel's breeding colonies up to 440 kilometres (270 mi) inland in Antarctica.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The highest bird diversity occurs in tropical regions.
[src:bird/bird-p01] It was earlier thought that this high diversity was the result of higher speciation rates in the tropics; however studies from the 2000s found higher speciation rates in the high latitudes that were offset by greater extinction rates than in the tropics.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many species migrate annually over great distances and across oceans; several families of birds have adapted to life both on the world's oceans and in them, and some seabird species come ashore only to breed, while some penguins have been recorded diving up to 300 metres (980 ft) deep.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many bird species have established breeding populations in areas to which they have been introduced by humans.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Some of these introductions have been deliberate; the ring-necked pheasant, for example, has been introduced around the world as a game bird.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Others have been accidental, such as the establishment of wild monk parakeets in several North American cities after their escape from captivity.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Some species, including cattle egret, yellow-headed caracara and galah, have spread naturally far beyond their original ranges as agricultural expansion created alternative habitats although modern practices of intensive agriculture have negatively impacted farmland bird populations.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Compared with other vertebrates, birds have a body plan that shows many unusual adaptations, mostly to facilitate flight.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The skeleton consists of very lightweight bones.
[src:bird/bird-p01] They have large air-filled cavities (called pneumatic cavities) which connect with the respiratory system.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The skull bones in adults are fused and do not show cranial sutures.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The orbital cavities that house the eyeballs are large and separated from each other by a bony septum (partition).
[src:bird/bird-p01] The spine has cervical, thoracic, lumbar and caudal regions with the number of cervical (neck) vertebrae highly variable and especially flexible, but movement is reduced in the anterior thoracic vertebrae and absent in the later vertebrae.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The last few are fused with the pelvis to form the synsacrum.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The ribs are flattened and the sternum is keeled for the attachment of flight muscles except in the flightless bird orders.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The wings are more or less developed depending on the species; the only known groups that lost their wings are the extinct moa and elephant birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Like reptiles, birds are primarily uricotelic; that is, their kidneys extract nitrogenous waste from their bloodstream and excrete it as uric acid, instead of urea or ammonia, through the ureters into the intestine.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds do not have a urinary bladder or external urethral opening.
[src:bird/bird-p01] With the exception of the ostrich, uric acid is excreted along with faeces as a semisolid waste.
[src:bird/bird-p01] However, birds such as hummingbirds can be facultatively ammonotelic, excreting most of the nitrogenous wastes as ammonia.
[src:bird/bird-p01] They also excrete creatine, rather than creatinine like mammals.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This material, as well as the output of the intestines, emerges from the bird's cloaca.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The cloaca is a multi-purpose opening: waste is expelled through it, most birds mate by joining cloaca, and females lay eggs from it.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In addition, many species of birds regurgitate pellets.
[src:bird/bird-p01] It is a common but not universal feature of altricial passerine nestlings (born helpless, under constant parental care) that instead of excreting directly into the nest, they produce a fecal sac.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This is a mucus-covered pouch that allows parents to either dispose of the waste outside the nest or to recycle the waste through their own digestive system.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most male birds do not have intromittent penises.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Males within Palaeognathae (with the exception of the kiwis), the Anseriformes (with the exception of screamers), and in rudimentary forms in Galliformes (but fully developed in Cracidae) possess a penis, which is never present in Neoaves.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Its length is thought to be related to sperm competition and it fills with lymphatic fluid instead of blood when erect.
[src:bird/bird-p01] When not copulating, it is hidden within the proctodeum compartment within the cloaca, just inside the vent.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Female birds have sperm storage tubules that allow sperm to remain viable long after copulation, a hundred days in some species.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Sperm from multiple males may compete through this mechanism.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most female birds have a single ovary and a single oviduct, both on the left side, but there are exceptions: species in at least 16 different orders of birds have two ovaries.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Even these species, however, tend to have a single oviduct.
[src:bird/bird-p01] It has been speculated that this might be an adaptation to flight, but males have two testes, and it is also observed that the gonads in both sexes decrease dramatically in size outside the breeding season.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Also, terrestrial birds generally have a single ovary, as does the platypus, an egg-laying mammal.
[src:bird/bird-p01] A more likely explanation is that the egg develops a shell while passing through the oviduct over a period of about a day, so that if two eggs were to develop at the same time, there would be a risk to survival.
[src:bird/bird-p01] While rare, mostly abortive, parthenogenesis is not unknown in birds and eggs can be diploid, automictic and results in male offspring.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds are solely gonochoric, meaning they have two sexes: either female or male.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The sex of birds follows the Z and W sex-determination system, where the ovum determines the sex of the offspring.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Male birds have two Z chromosomes (ZZ), and female birds have a W chromosome and a Z chromosome (WZ).
[src:bird/bird-p01] In mammals, by contrast, the sperm determines the sex of the offspring in the X and Y sex-determination system.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In all species of birds, an individual's sex is determined at fertilisation.
[src:bird/bird-p01] One 2007 study claimed to demonstrate temperature-dependent sex determination among the Australian brushturkey, for which higher temperatures during incubation resulted in a higher female-to-male sex ratio.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This, however, was later proven to not be the case.
[src:bird/bird-p01] These birds do not exhibit temperature-dependent sex determination, but temperature-dependent sex mortality.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds have one of the most complex respiratory systems of all animal groups.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Upon inhalation, 75% of the fresh air bypasses the lungs and flows directly into a posterior air sac which extends from the lungs and connects with air spaces in the bones and fills them with air.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The other 25% of the air goes directly into the lungs.
[src:bird/bird-p01] When the bird exhales, the used air flows out of the lungs and the stored fresh air from the posterior air sac is simultaneously forced into the lungs.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Thus, a bird's lungs receive a constant supply of fresh air during both inhalation and exhalation.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Sound production is achieved using the syrinx, a muscular chamber incorporating multiple tympanic membranes which diverges from the lower end of the trachea; the trachea being elongated in some species, increasing the volume of vocalisations and the perception of the bird's size.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In birds, the main arteries taking blood away from the heart originate from the right aortic arch (or pharyngeal arch), unlike in the mammals where the left aortic arch forms this part of the aorta.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The postcava receives blood from the limbs via the renal portal system.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Unlike in mammals, the circulating red blood cells in birds retain their nucleus.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The avian circulatory system is driven by a four-chambered, myogenic heart contained in a fibrous pericardial sac.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This pericardial sac is filled with a serous fluid for lubrication.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The heart itself is divided into a right and left half, each with an atrium and ventricle.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The atrium and ventricles of each side are separated by atrioventricular valves which prevent back flow from one chamber to the next during contraction.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Being myogenic, the heart's pace is maintained by pacemaker cells found in the sinoatrial node, located on the right atrium.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The sinoatrial node uses calcium to cause a depolarising signal transduction pathway from the atrium through right and left atrioventricular bundle which communicates contraction to the ventricles.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The avian heart also consists of muscular arches that are made up of thick bundles of muscular layers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Much like a mammalian heart, the avian heart is composed of endocardial, myocardial and epicardial layers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The atrium walls tend to be thinner than the ventricle walls, due to the intense ventricular contraction used to pump oxygenated blood throughout the body.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Avian hearts are generally larger than mammalian hearts when compared to body mass.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This adaptation allows more blood to be pumped to meet the high metabolic need associated with flight.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds have a very efficient system for diffusing oxygen into the blood; birds have a ten times greater surface area to gas exchange volume than mammals.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As a result, birds have more blood in their capillaries per unit of volume of lung than a mammal.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The arteries are composed of thick elastic muscles to withstand the pressure of the ventricular contractions, and become more rigid as they move away from the heart.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Blood moves through the arteries, which undergo vasoconstriction, and into arterioles which act as a transportation system to distribute primarily oxygen as well as nutrients to all tissues of the body.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As the arterioles move away from the heart and into individual organs and tissues they are further divided to increase surface area and slow blood flow.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Blood travels through the arterioles and moves into the capillaries where gas exchange can occur.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Capillaries are organised into capillary beds in tissues; it is here that blood exchanges oxygen for carbon dioxide waste.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In the capillary beds, blood flow is slowed to allow maximum diffusion of oxygen into the tissues.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Once the blood has become deoxygenated, it travels through venules then veins and back to the heart.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Veins, unlike arteries, are thin and rigid as they do not need to withstand extreme pressure.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As blood travels through the venules to the veins a funnelling occurs called vasodilation bringing blood back to the heart.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Once the blood reaches the heart, it moves first into the right atrium, then the right ventricle to be pumped through the lungs for further gas exchange of carbon dioxide waste for oxygen.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Oxygenated blood then flows from the lungs through the left atrium to the left ventricle where it is pumped out to the body.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The nervous system is large relative to the bird's size.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The most developed part of the brain of birds is the one that controls the flight-related functions, while the cerebellum coordinates movement and the cerebrum controls behaviour patterns, navigation, mating and nest building.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most birds have a poor sense of smell with notable exceptions including kiwis, New World vultures and tubenoses.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The avian visual system is usually highly developed.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Water birds have special flexible lenses, allowing accommodation for vision in air and water.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds are tetrachromatic, possessing ultraviolet (UV) sensitive cone cells in the eye as well as green, red and blue ones.
[src:bird/bird-p01] They also have double cones, likely to mediate achromatic vision.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Many birds show plumage patterns in ultraviolet that are invisible to the human eye; some birds whose sexes appear similar to the naked eye are distinguished by the presence of ultraviolet reflective patches on their feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Male blue tits have an ultraviolet reflective crown patch which is displayed in courtship by posturing and raising of their nape feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Ultraviolet light is also used in foraging—kestrels have been shown to search for prey by detecting the UV fluorescent urine trail marks left on the ground by rodents.
[src:bird/bird-p01] With the exception of pigeons and a few other species, the eyelids of birds are not used in blinking.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Instead the eye is lubricated by the nictitating membrane, a third eyelid that moves horizontally.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The nictitating membrane also covers the eye and acts as a contact lens in many aquatic birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The bird retina has a fan shaped blood supply system called the pecten.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Eyes of most birds are large, not very round and capable of only limited movement in the orbits, typically 10–20°.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds with eyes on the sides of their heads have a wide visual field, while birds with eyes on the front of their heads, such as owls, have binocular vision and can estimate the depth of field.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The avian ear lacks external pinnae but is covered by feathers, although in some birds, such as the *Asio*, *Bubo* and *Otus* owls, these feathers form tufts which resemble ears.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The inner ear has a cochlea, but it is not a spiral as in mammals.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Several species have been demonstrated to hear infrasound (below 20 Hz) and a few cave-dwelling swifts and oilbirds emit ultrasound (above 20 kHz) and echolocate in darkness.
[src:bird/bird-p01] A few species are able to use chemical defences against predators; some Procellariiformes can eject an unpleasant stomach oil against an aggressor, and some species of pitohuis from New Guinea have a powerful neurotoxin in their skin and feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] A lack of field observations limit our knowledge, but intraspecific conflicts are known to sometimes result in injury or death.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The screamers (Anhimidae), some jacanas (*Jacana*, *Hydrophasianus*), the spur-winged goose (*Plectropterus*), the torrent duck (*Merganetta*) and nine species of lapwing (*Vanellus*) use a sharp spur on the wing as a weapon.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The steamer ducks (*Tachyeres*), geese and swans (*Anserinae*), the solitaire (*Pezophaps*), sheathbills (*Chionis*), some guans (*Crax*) and stone curlews (*Burhinus*) use a bony knob on the alular metacarpal to punch and hammer opponents.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The jacanas *Actophilornis* and *Irediparra* have an expanded, blade-like radius.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The extinct *Xenicibis* was unique in having an elongate forelimb and massive hand which likely functioned in combat or defence as a jointed club or flail.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Swans, for instance, may strike with the bony spurs and bite when defending eggs or young.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Feathers are a feature characteristic of birds (though also present in some dinosaurs not currently considered to be true birds).
[src:bird/bird-p01] They facilitate flight, provide insulation that aids in thermoregulation, and are used in display, camouflage, and signalling.
[src:bird/bird-p01] There are several types of feathers, each serving its own set of purposes.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Feathers are epidermal growths attached to the skin and arise only in specific tracts of skin called pterylae.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The distribution pattern of these feather tracts (pterylosis) is used in taxonomy and systematics.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The arrangement and appearance of feathers on the body, called plumage, may vary within species by age, social status, and sex.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Moulting is annual in most species, although some may have two moults a year, and large birds of prey may moult only once every few years.
[src:bird/bird-p01] In passerines, flight feathers are replaced one at a time with the innermost *primary* being the first.
[src:bird/bird-p01] When the fifth of sixth primary is replaced, the outermost *tertiaries* begin to drop.
[src:bird/bird-p01] After the innermost tertiaries are moulted, the *secondaries* starting from the innermost begin to drop and this proceeds to the outer feathers (centrifugal moult).
[src:bird/bird-p01] The greater primary *coverts* are moulted in synchrony with the primary that they overlap.
[src:bird/bird-p01] A small number of species, such as ducks and geese, lose all of their flight feathers at once, temporarily becoming flightless.
[src:bird/bird-p01] As a general rule, the tail feathers are moulted and replaced starting with the innermost pair.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Centripetal moults of tail feathers are however seen in the Phasianidae.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The centrifugal moult is modified in the tail feathers of woodpeckers and treecreepers, in that it begins with the second innermost pair of feathers and finishes with the central pair of feathers so that the bird maintains a functional climbing tail.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The general pattern seen in passerines is that the primaries are replaced outward, secondaries inward, and the tail from centre outward.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Before nesting, the females of most bird species gain a bare brood patch by losing feathers close to the belly.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The skin there is well supplied with blood vessels and helps the bird in incubation.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Feathers require maintenance and birds preen or groom them daily, spending an average of around 9% of their daily time on this.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The bill is used to brush away foreign particles and to apply waxy secretions from the uropygial gland; these secretions protect the feathers' flexibility and act as an antimicrobial agent, inhibiting the growth of feather-degrading bacteria.
[src:bird/bird-p01] This may be supplemented with the secretions of formic acid from ants, which birds receive through a behaviour known as anting, to remove feather parasites.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The scales of birds are composed of the same keratin as beaks, claws, and spurs.
[src:bird/bird-p01] They are found mainly on the toes and metatarsus, but may be found further up on the ankle in some birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most bird scales do not overlap significantly, except in the cases of kingfishers and woodpeckers.
[src:bird/bird-p01] The scales of birds are thought to be homologous to those of reptiles and mammals.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Most birds can fly, which distinguishes them from almost all other vertebrate classes.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Flight is the primary means of locomotion for most bird species and is used for searching for food and for escaping from predators.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Birds have various adaptations for flight, including a lightweight skeleton, two large flight muscles, the pectoralis (which accounts for 15% of the total mass of the bird) and the supracoracoideus, as well as a modified forelimb (wing) that serves as an aerofoil.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Wing shape and size generally determine a bird's flight style and performance; many birds combine powered, flapping flight with less energy-intensive soaring flight.
[src:bird/bird-p01] About 60 extant bird species are flightless, as were many extinct birds.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Flightlessness often arises in birds on isolated islands, most likely due to limited resources and the absence of mammalian land predators.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Flightlessness is almost exclusively correlated with gigantism due to an island's inherent condition of isolation.
[src:bird/bird-p01] Although flightless, penguins use similar musculature and movements to "fly" through the water, as do some flight-capable birds such as auks, shearwaters and dippers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Most birds are diurnal, but some birds, such as many species of owls and nightjars, are nocturnal or crepuscular (active during twilight hours), and many coastal waders feed when the tides are appropriate, by day or night.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds that employ many strategies to obtain food or feed on a variety of food items are called generalists, while others that concentrate time and effort on specific food items or have a single strategy to obtain food are considered specialists.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Avian foraging strategies can vary widely by species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many birds glean for insects, invertebrates, fruit, or seeds.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some hunt insects by suddenly attacking from a branch.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Those species that seek pest insects are considered beneficial 'biological control agents' and their presence encouraged in biological pest control programmes.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Combined, insectivorous birds eat 400–500 million metric tons of arthropods annually.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Nectar feeders such as hummingbirds, sunbirds, lories, and lorikeets amongst others have specially adapted brushy tongues and in many cases bills designed to fit co-adapted flowers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Kiwis and shorebirds with long bills probe for invertebrates; shorebirds' varied bill lengths and feeding methods result in the separation of ecological niches.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Divers, diving ducks, penguins and auks pursue their prey underwater, using their wings or feet for propulsion, while aerial predators such as sulids, kingfishers and terns plunge dive after their prey.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Flamingos, three species of prion, and some ducks are filter feeders.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Geese and dabbling ducks are primarily grazers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some species, including frigatebirds, gulls, and skuas, engage in kleptoparasitism, stealing food items from other birds.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Kleptoparasitism is thought to be a supplement to food obtained by hunting, rather than a significant part of any species' diet; a study of great frigatebirds stealing from masked boobies estimated that the frigatebirds stole at most 40% of their food and on average stole only 5%.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other birds are scavengers; some of these, like vultures, are specialised carrion eaters, while others, like gulls, corvids, or other birds of prey, are opportunists.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Water is needed by many birds although their mode of excretion and lack of sweat glands reduces the physiological demands.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some desert birds can obtain their water needs entirely from moisture in their food.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some have other adaptations such as allowing their body temperature to rise, saving on moisture loss from evaporative cooling or panting.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Seabirds can drink seawater and have salt glands inside the head that eliminate excess salt out of the nostrils.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Most birds scoop water in their beaks and raise their head to let water run down the throat.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some species, especially of arid zones, belonging to the pigeon, finch, mousebird, button-quail and bustard families are capable of sucking up water without the need to tilt back their heads.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some desert birds depend on water sources and sandgrouse are particularly well known for congregating daily at waterholes.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Nesting sandgrouse and many plovers carry water to their young by wetting their belly feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some birds carry water for chicks at the nest in their crop or regurgitate it along with food.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The pigeon family, flamingos and penguins have adaptations to produce a nutritive fluid called crop milk that they provide to their chicks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many bird species migrate to take advantage of global differences of seasonal temperatures, therefore optimising availability of food sources and breeding habitat.
[src:bird/bird-p02] These migrations vary among the different groups.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many landbirds, shorebirds, and waterbirds undertake annual long-distance migrations, usually triggered by the length of daylight as well as weather conditions.
[src:bird/bird-p02] These birds are characterised by a breeding season spent in the temperate or polar regions and a non-breeding season in the tropical regions or opposite hemisphere.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Before migration, birds substantially increase body fats and reserves and reduce the size of some of their organs.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Migration is highly demanding energetically, particularly as birds need to cross deserts and oceans without refuelling.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Landbirds have a flight range of around 2,500 km (1,600 mi) and shorebirds can fly up to 4,000 km (2,500 mi), although the bar-tailed godwit is capable of non-stop flights of up to 10,200 km (6,300 mi).
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other seabirds disperse after breeding, travelling widely but having no set migration route.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Albatrosses nesting in the Southern Ocean often undertake circumpolar trips between breeding seasons.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some bird species undertake shorter migrations, travelling only as far as is required to avoid bad weather or obtain food.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Irruptive species such as the boreal finches are one such group and can commonly be found at a location in one year and absent the next.
[src:bird/bird-p02] This type of migration is normally associated with food availability.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Species may also travel shorter distances over part of their range, with individuals from higher latitudes travelling into the existing range of conspecifics; others undertake partial migrations, where only a fraction of the population, usually females and subdominant males, migrates.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Partial migration can form a large percentage of the migration behaviour of birds in some regions; in Australia, surveys found that 44% of non-passerine birds and 32% of passerines were partially migratory.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Altitudinal migration is a form of short-distance migration in which birds spend the breeding season at higher altitudes and move to lower ones during suboptimal conditions.
[src:bird/bird-p02] It is most often triggered by temperature changes and usually occurs when the normal territories also become inhospitable due to lack of food.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some species may also be nomadic, holding no fixed territory and moving according to weather and food availability.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Parrots as a family are overwhelmingly neither migratory nor sedentary but considered to either be dispersive, irruptive, nomadic or undertake small and irregular migrations.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The ability of birds to return to precise locations across vast distances has been known for some time; in an experiment conducted in the 1950s, a Manx shearwater released in Boston in the United States returned to its colony in Skomer, in Wales within 13 days, a distance of 5,150 km (3,200 mi).
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds navigate during migration using a variety of methods.
[src:bird/bird-p02] For diurnal migrants, the sun is used to navigate by day, and a stellar compass is used at night.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds that use the sun compensate for the changing position of the sun during the day by the use of an internal clock.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Orientation with the stellar compass depends on the position of the constellations surrounding Polaris.
[src:bird/bird-p02] These are backed up in some species by their ability to sense the Earth's geomagnetism through specialised photoreceptors.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds communicate primarily using visual and auditory signals.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Signals can be interspecific (between species) and intraspecific (within species).
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds sometimes use plumage to assess and assert social dominance, to display breeding condition in sexually selected species, or to make threatening displays, as in the sunbittern's mimicry of a large predator to ward off hawks and protect young chicks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Visual communication among birds may also involve ritualised displays, which have developed from non-signalling actions such as preening, the adjustments of feather position, pecking, or other behaviour.
[src:bird/bird-p02] These displays may signal aggression or submission or may contribute to the formation of pair-bonds.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The most elaborate displays occur during courtship, where "dances" are often formed from complex combinations of many possible component movements; males' breeding success may depend on the quality of such displays.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Bird calls and songs, which are produced in the syrinx, are the major means by which birds communicate with sound.
[src:bird/bird-p02] This communication can be very complex; some species can operate the two sides of the syrinx independently, allowing the simultaneous production of two different songs.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some birds also use mechanical sounds for auditory communication.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The *Coenocorypha* snipes of New Zealand drive air through their feathers, woodpeckers drum for long-distance communication, and palm cockatoos use tools to drum.
[src:bird/bird-p02] While some birds are essentially territorial or live in small family groups, other birds may form large flocks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The principal benefits of flocking are safety in numbers and increased foraging efficiency.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Defence against predators is particularly important in closed habitats like forests, where ambush predation is common and multiple eyes can provide a valuable early warning system.
[src:bird/bird-p02] This has led to the development of many mixed-species feeding flocks, which are usually composed of small numbers of many species; these flocks provide safety in numbers but increase potential competition for resources.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Costs of flocking include bullying of socially subordinate birds by more dominant birds and the reduction of feeding efficiency in certain cases.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some species have a mixed system with breeding pairs maintaining territories, while unmated or young birds live in flocks where they secure mates prior to finding territories.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds sometimes also form associations with non-avian species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Plunge-diving seabirds associate with dolphins and tuna, which push shoaling fish towards the surface.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some species of hornbills have a mutualistic relationship with dwarf mongooses, in which they forage together and warn each other of nearby birds of prey and other predators.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The high metabolic rates of birds during the active part of the day is supplemented by rest at other times.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Sleeping birds often use a type of sleep known as vigilant sleep, where periods of rest are interspersed with quick eye-opening "peeks", allowing them to be sensitive to disturbances and enable rapid escape from threats.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Swifts are believed to be able to sleep in flight and radar observations suggest that they orient themselves to face the wind in their roosting flight.
[src:bird/bird-p02] It has been suggested that there may be certain kinds of sleep which are possible even when in flight.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some birds have also demonstrated the capacity to fall into slow-wave sleep one hemisphere of the brain at a time.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The birds tend to exercise this ability depending upon its position relative to the outside of the flock.
[src:bird/bird-p02] This may allow the eye opposite the sleeping hemisphere to remain vigilant for predators by viewing the outer margins of the flock.
[src:bird/bird-p02] This adaptation is also known from marine mammals.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Communal roosting is common because it lowers the loss of body heat and decreases the risks associated with predators.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Roosting sites are often chosen with regard to thermoregulation and safety.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Unusual mobile roost sites include large herbivores on the African savanna that are used by oxpeckers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many sleeping birds bend their heads over their backs and tuck their bills in their back feathers, although others place their beaks among their breast feathers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many birds rest on one leg, while some may pull up their legs into their feathers, especially in cold weather.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Perching birds have a tendon-locking mechanism that helps them hold on to the perch when they are asleep.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many ground birds, such as quails and pheasants, roost in trees.
[src:bird/bird-p02] A few parrots of the genus *Loriculus* roost hanging upside down.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some hummingbirds go into a nightly state of torpor accompanied with a reduction of their metabolic rates.
[src:bird/bird-p02] This physiological adaptation shows in nearly a hundred other species, including owlet-nightjars, nightjars, and woodswallows.
[src:bird/bird-p02] One species, the common poorwill, even enters a state of hibernation.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds do not have sweat glands, but can lose water directly through the skin, and they may cool themselves by moving to shade, standing in water, panting, increasing their surface area, fluttering their throat or using special behaviours like urohidrosis to cool themselves.
[src:bird/bird-p02] 95 per cent of bird species are socially monogamous.
[src:bird/bird-p02] These species pair for at least the length of the breeding season or—in some cases—for several years or until the death of one mate.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Monogamy allows for both paternal care and biparental care, which is especially important for species in which care from both the female and the male parent is required in order to successfully rear a brood.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Among many socially monogamous species, extra-pair copulation (infidelity) is common.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Such behaviour typically occurs between dominant males and females paired with subordinate males, but may also be the result of forced copulation in ducks and other anatids.
[src:bird/bird-p02] For females, possible benefits of extra-pair copulation include getting better genes for her offspring and insuring against the possibility of infertility in her mate.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Males of species that engage in extra-pair copulations will closely guard their mates to ensure the parentage of the offspring that they raise.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other mating systems, including polygyny, polyandry, polygamy, polygynandry, and promiscuity, also occur.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Polygamous breeding systems arise when females are able to raise broods without the help of males.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Mating systems vary across bird families but variations within species are thought to be driven by environmental conditions.
[src:bird/bird-p02] A unique system is the formation of trios where a third individual is allowed by a breeding pair temporarily into the territory to assist with brood raising thereby leading to higher fitness.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Breeding usually involves some form of courtship display, typically performed by the male.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Most displays are rather simple and involve some type of song.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some displays, however, are quite elaborate.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Depending on the species, these may include wing or tail drumming, dancing, aerial flights, or communal lekking.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Females are generally the ones that drive partner selection, although in the polyandrous phalaropes, this is reversed: plainer males choose brightly coloured females.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Courtship feeding, billing and *allopreening* are commonly performed between partners, generally after the birds have paired and mated.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Homosexual behaviour has been observed in males or females in numerous species of birds, including copulation, pair-bonding, and joint parenting of chicks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Over 130 avian species around the world engage in sexual interactions between the same sex or homosexual behaviours.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many birds actively defend a territory from others of the same species during the breeding season; maintenance of territories protects the food source for their chicks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Species that are unable to defend feeding territories, such as seabirds and swifts, often breed in colonies instead; this is thought to offer protection from predators.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Colonial breeders defend small nesting sites, and competition between and within species for nesting sites can be intense.
[src:bird/bird-p02] All birds lay amniotic eggs with hard shells made mostly of calcium carbonate.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Hole and burrow nesting species tend to lay white or pale eggs, while open nesters lay camouflaged eggs.
[src:bird/bird-p02] There are many exceptions to this pattern, however; the ground-nesting nightjars have pale eggs, and camouflage is instead provided by their plumage.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Species that are victims of brood parasites have varying egg colours to improve the chances of spotting a parasite's egg, which forces female parasites to match their eggs to those of their hosts.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Most species create somewhat elaborate nests, which can be cups, domes, plates, mounds, or burrows.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some bird nests can be a simple scrape, with minimal or no lining; most seabird and wader nests are no more than a scrape on the ground.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Most birds build nests in sheltered, hidden areas to avoid predation, but large or colonial birds—which are more capable of defence—may build more open nests.
[src:bird/bird-p02] During nest construction, some species seek out plant matter from plants with parasite-reducing toxins to improve chick survival, and feathers are often used for nest insulation.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some bird species have no nests; the cliff-nesting common guillemot lays its eggs on bare rock, and male emperor penguins keep eggs between their body and feet.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The absence of nests is especially prevalent in open habitat ground-nesting species where any addition of nest material would make the nest more conspicuous.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many ground nesting birds lay a clutch of eggs that hatch synchronously, with precocial chicks led away from the nests (nidifugous) by their parents soon after hatching.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Incubation, which regulates temperature for chick development, usually begins after the last egg has been laid.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In monogamous species incubation duties are often shared, whereas in polygamous species one parent is wholly responsible for incubation.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Warmth from parents passes to the eggs through brood patches, areas of bare skin on the abdomen or breast of the incubating birds.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Incubation can be an energetically demanding process; adult albatrosses, for instance, lose as much as 83 grams (2.9 oz) of body weight per day of incubation.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The warmth for the incubation of the eggs of megapodes comes from the sun, decaying vegetation or volcanic sources.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Incubation periods range from 10 days (in woodpeckers, cuckoos and passerine birds) to over 80 days (in albatrosses and kiwis).
[src:bird/bird-p02] The diversity of characteristics of birds is great, sometimes even in closely related species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Several avian characteristics are compared in the table below.
[src:bird/bird-p02] At the time of their hatching, chicks range in development from helpless to independent, depending on their species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Helpless chicks are termed *altricial*, and tend to be born small, blind, immobile and naked; chicks that are mobile and feathered upon hatching are termed *precocial*.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Altricial chicks need help thermoregulating and must be brooded for longer than precocial chicks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The young of many bird species do not precisely fit into either the precocial or altricial category, having some aspects of each and thus fall somewhere on an "altricial-precocial spectrum".
[src:bird/bird-p02] Chicks at neither extreme but favouring one or the other may be termed *semi-precocial* or *semi-altricial*.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The length and nature of parental care varies widely amongst different orders and species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] At one extreme, parental care in megapodes ends at hatching; the newly hatched chick digs itself out of the nest mound without parental assistance and can fend for itself immediately.
[src:bird/bird-p02] At the other extreme, many seabirds have extended periods of parental care, the longest being that of the great frigatebird, whose chicks take up to six months to fledge and are fed by the parents for up to an additional 14 months.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The *chick guard stage* describes the period of breeding during which one of the adult birds is permanently present at the nest after chicks have hatched.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The main purpose of the guard stage is to aid offspring to thermoregulate and protect them from predation.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In some species, both parents care for nestlings and fledglings; in others, such care is the responsibility of only one sex.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In some species, other members of the same species—usually close relatives of the breeding pair, such as offspring from previous broods—will help with the raising of the young.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Such alloparenting is particularly common among the Corvida, which includes such birds as the true crows, Australian magpie and fairy-wrens, but has been observed in species as different as the rifleman and red kite.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Among most groups of animals, male parental care is rare.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In birds, however, it is quite common—more so than in any other vertebrate class.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Although territory and nest site defence, incubation, and chick feeding are often shared tasks, there is sometimes a division of labour in which one mate undertakes all or most of a particular duty.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The point at which chicks fledge varies dramatically.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The chicks of the *Synthliboramphus* murrelets, like the ancient murrelet, leave the nest the night after they hatch, following their parents out to sea, where they are raised away from terrestrial predators.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some other species, such as ducks, move their chicks away from the nest at an early age.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In most species, chicks leave the nest just before, or soon after, they are able to fly.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The amount of parental care after fledging varies; albatross chicks leave the nest on their own and receive no further help, while other species continue some supplementary feeding after fledging.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Chicks may also follow their parents during their first migration.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Brood parasitism, in which an egg-layer leaves her eggs with another individual's brood, is more common among birds than any other type of organism.
[src:bird/bird-p02] After a parasitic bird lays her eggs in another bird's nest, they are often accepted and raised by the host at the expense of the host's own brood.
[src:bird/bird-p02] One hundred bird species, including honeyguides, icterids, and ducks, are obligate parasites, though the most famous are the cuckoos.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some brood parasites are adapted to hatch before their host's young, which allows them to destroy the host's eggs by pushing them out of the nest or to kill the host's chicks; this ensures that all food brought to the nest will be fed to the parasitic chicks.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds have evolved a variety of mating behaviours, with the peacock tail being perhaps the most famous example of sexual selection and the Fisherian runaway.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Commonly occurring sexual dimorphisms such as size and colour differences are energetically costly attributes that signal competitive breeding situations.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many types of avian sexual selection have been identified; intersexual selection, also known as female choice; and intrasexual competition, where individuals of the more abundant sex compete with each other for the privilege to mate.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Sexually selected traits often evolve to become more pronounced in competitive breeding situations until the trait begins to limit the individual's fitness.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Conflicts between an individual fitness and signalling adaptations ensure that sexually selected ornaments such as plumage colouration and courtship behaviour are "honest" traits.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Signals must be costly to ensure that only good-quality individuals can present these exaggerated sexual ornaments and behaviours.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Inbreeding causes early death (inbreeding depression) in the zebra finch *Taeniopygia guttata*.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Embryo survival (that is, hatching success of fertile eggs) was significantly lower for sib-sib mating pairs than for unrelated pairs.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Darwin's finch *Geospiza scandens* experiences inbreeding depression (reduced survival of offspring) and the magnitude of this effect is influenced by environmental conditions such as low food availability.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Incestuous matings by the purple-crowned fairy wren *Malurus coronatus* result in severe fitness costs due to inbreeding depression (greater than 30% reduction in hatchability of eggs).
[src:bird/bird-p02] Females paired with related males may undertake extra pair matings (see Promiscuity#Other animals for 90% frequency in avian species) that can reduce the negative effects of inbreeding.
[src:bird/bird-p02] However, there are ecological and demographic constraints on extra pair matings.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Nevertheless, 43% of broods produced by incestuously paired females contained extra pair young.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Inbreeding depression occurs in the great tit (*Parus major*) when the offspring produced as a result of a mating between close relatives show reduced fitness.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In natural populations of *Parus major*, inbreeding is avoided by dispersal of individuals from their birthplace, which reduces the chance of mating with a close relative.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Southern pied babblers *Turdoides bicolor* appear to avoid inbreeding in two ways.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The first is through dispersal, and the second is by avoiding familiar group members as mates.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Cooperative breeding in birds typically occurs when offspring, usually males, delay dispersal from their natal group in order to remain with the family to help rear younger kin.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Female offspring rarely stay at home, dispersing over distances that allow them to breed independently, or to join unrelated groups.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In general, inbreeding is avoided because it leads to a reduction in progeny fitness (inbreeding depression) due largely to the homozygous expression of deleterious recessive alleles.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Cross-fertilisation between unrelated individuals ordinarily leads to the masking of deleterious recessive alleles in progeny.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds occupy a wide range of ecological positions.
[src:bird/bird-p02] While some birds are generalists, others are highly specialised in their habitat or food requirements.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Even within a single habitat, such as a forest, the niches occupied by different species of birds vary, with some species feeding in the forest canopy, others beneath the canopy, and still others on the forest floor.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Forest birds may be insectivores, frugivores, or nectarivores.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Aquatic birds generally feed by fishing, plant eating, and piracy or kleptoparasitism.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds of prey specialise in hunting mammals or other birds, while vultures are specialised scavengers.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds are also preyed upon by a range of mammals including a few avivorous bats.
[src:bird/bird-p02] A wide range of endo- and ectoparasites depend on birds and some parasites that are transmitted from parent to young have co-evolved and show host-specificity.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some nectar-feeding birds are important pollinators, and many frugivores play a key role in seed dispersal.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Plants and pollinating birds often coevolve, and in some cases a flower's primary pollinator is the only species capable of reaching its nectar.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds are often important to island ecology.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds have frequently reached islands that mammals have not; on those islands, birds may fulfil ecological roles typically played by larger animals.
[src:bird/bird-p02] For example, in New Zealand nine species of moa were important browsers, as are the kererū and kōkako today.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Today the plants of New Zealand retain the defensive adaptations evolved to protect them from the extinct moa.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many birds act as ecosystem engineers through the construction of nests, which provide important microhabitats and food for hundreds of species of invertebrates.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Nesting seabirds may affect the ecology of islands and surrounding seas, principally through the concentration of large quantities of guano, which may enrich the local soil and the surrounding seas.
[src:bird/bird-p02] A wide variety of avian ecology field methods, including counts, nest monitoring, and capturing and marking, are used for researching avian ecology.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Since birds are highly visible and common animals, humans have had a relationship with them since the dawn of man.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Sometimes, these relationships are mutualistic, like the cooperative honey-gathering among honeyguides and African peoples such as the Borana.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other times, they may be commensal, as when species such as the house sparrow have benefited from human activities.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Several species have reconciled to habits of farmers who practice traditional farming.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Examples include the Sarus Crane that begins nesting in India when farmers flood the fields in anticipation of rains, and the woolly-necked storks that have taken to nesting on a short tree grown for agroforestry beside fields and canals.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Several bird species have become commercially significant agricultural pests, and some pose an aviation hazard.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Human activities can also be detrimental, and have threatened numerous bird species with extinction (hunting, avian lead poisoning, pesticides, roadkill, wind turbine kills and predation by pet cats and dogs are common causes of death for birds).
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds can act as vectors for spreading diseases such as psittacosis, salmonellosis, campylobacteriosis, mycobacteriosis (avian tuberculosis), avian influenza (bird flu), giardiasis, and cryptosporidiosis over long distances.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some of these are zoonotic diseases that can also be transmitted to humans.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Domesticated birds raised for meat and eggs, called poultry, are the largest source of animal protein eaten by humans; in 2003, 76 million tons of poultry and 61 million tons of eggs were produced worldwide.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Chickens account for much of human poultry consumption, though domesticated turkeys, ducks, and geese are also relatively common.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many species of birds are also hunted for meat.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Bird hunting is primarily a recreational activity except in extremely undeveloped areas.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The most important birds hunted in North and South America are waterfowl; other widely hunted birds include pheasants, wild turkeys, quail, doves, partridge, grouse, snipe, and woodcock.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Muttonbirding is also popular in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Although some hunting, such as that of muttonbirds, may be sustainable, hunting has led to the extinction or endangerment of dozens of species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other commercially valuable products from birds include feathers (especially the down of geese and ducks), which are used as insulation in clothing and bedding, and seabird faeces (guano), which is a valuable source of phosphorus and nitrogen.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The War of the Pacific, sometimes called the Guano War, was fought in part over the control of guano deposits.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds have been domesticated by humans both as pets and for practical purposes.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Colourful birds, such as parrots and mynas, are bred in captivity or kept as pets, a practice that has led to the illegal trafficking of some endangered species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Falcons and cormorants have long been used for hunting and fishing, respectively.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Messenger pigeons, used since at least 1 AD, remained important as recently as World War II.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Today, such activities are more common either as hobbies, for entertainment and tourism.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Amateur bird enthusiasts (called birdwatchers, twitchers or, more commonly, birders) number in the millions.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many homeowners erect bird feeders near their homes to attract various species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Bird feeding has grown into a multimillion-dollar industry; for example, an estimated 75% of households in Britain provide food for birds at some point during the winter.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds play prominent and diverse roles in religion and mythology.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In several civilisations of ancient Italy, particularly Etruscan and Roman religion, priests were involved in augury, or interpreting the words of birds while the "auspex" (from which the word "auspicious" is derived) watched their activities to foretell events.
[src:bird/bird-p02] They may also serve as religious symbols, as when Jonah (Hebrew: יונה, dove) embodied the fright, passivity, mourning, and beauty traditionally associated with doves.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds have themselves been deified, as in the case of the common peacock, which is perceived as Mother Earth by the people of southern India.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In the ancient world, doves were used as symbols of the Mesopotamian goddess Inanna (later known as Ishtar), the Canaanite mother goddess Asherah, and the Greek goddess Aphrodite.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In ancient Greece, Athena, the goddess of wisdom and patron deity of the city of Athens, had a little owl as her symbol.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In religious images preserved from the Inca and Tiwanaku empires, birds are depicted in the process of transgressing boundaries between earthly and underground spiritual realms.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Indigenous peoples of the central Andes maintain legends of birds passing to and from metaphysical worlds.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds have featured in culture and art since prehistoric times, when they were represented in early cave painting and carvings.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Some birds have been perceived as monsters, including the mythological Roc and the Māori's legendary *Pouākai*, a giant bird capable of snatching humans.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds were later used as symbols of power, as in the magnificent Peacock Throne of the Mughal and Persian emperors.
[src:bird/bird-p02] With the advent of scientific interest in birds, many paintings of birds were commissioned for books.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Among the most famous of these bird artists was John James Audubon, whose paintings of North American birds were a great commercial success in Europe and who later lent his name to the National Audubon Society.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds are also important figures in poetry; for example, Homer incorporated nightingales into his *Odyssey*, and Catullus used a sparrow as an erotic symbol in his Catullus 2.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The relationship between an albatross and a sailor is the central theme of Samuel Taylor Coleridge's *The Rime of the Ancient Mariner*, which led to the use of the term as a metaphor for a 'burden'.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other English metaphors derive from birds; vulture funds and vulture investors, for instance, take their name from the scavenging vulture.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Aircraft, particularly military aircraft, are frequently named after birds.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The predatory nature of raptors make them popular choices for fighter aircraft such as the F-16 Fighting Falcon and the Harrier Jump Jet, while the names of seabirds may be chosen for aircraft primarily used by naval forces such as the HU-16 Albatross and the V-22 Osprey.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Perceptions of bird species vary across cultures.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Owls are associated with bad luck, witchcraft, and death in parts of Africa, but are regarded as wise across much of Europe.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Hoopoes were considered sacred in Ancient Egypt and symbols of virtue in Persia, but were thought of as thieves across much of Europe and harbingers of war in Scandinavia.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In heraldry, birds, especially eagles, often appear in coats of arms In vexillology, birds are a popular choice on flags.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds feature in the flag designs of 17 countries and numerous subnational entities and territories.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds are used by nations to symbolise a country's identity and heritage, with 91 countries officially recognising a national bird.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Birds of prey are highly represented, though some nations have chosen other species of birds with parrots being popular among smaller, tropical nations.
[src:bird/bird-p02] A 2023 archaeological excavation of a 10,000-year-old site in Israel yielded hollow wing bones of coots and ducks with perforations made on the side that are thought to have allowed them to be used as flutes or whistles possibly used by Natufian people to lure birds of prey.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Human activities have caused population decreases or extinction in many bird species.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Over a hundred bird species have gone extinct in historical times, although the most dramatic human-caused avian extinctions, eradicating an estimated 750–1800 species, occurred during the human colonisation of Melanesian, Polynesian, and Micronesian islands.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Many bird populations are declining worldwide, with 1,227 species listed as threatened by BirdLife International and the IUCN in 2009.
[src:bird/bird-p02] There have been long-term declines in North American bird populations, with an estimated loss of 2.9 billion breeding adults, about 30% of the total, since 1970.
[src:bird/bird-p02] The most commonly cited human threat to birds is habitat loss.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Other threats include overhunting, collisions with buildings or vehicles, long-line fishing bycatch, pollution (including oil spills and pesticide use), competition and predation from nonnative invasive species, and climate change.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Governments and conservation groups work to protect birds, either by passing laws that preserve and restore bird habitat or by establishing captive populations for reintroductions.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Such projects have produced some successes; one study estimated that conservation efforts saved 16 species of bird that would otherwise have gone extinct between 1994 and 2004, including the California condor and Norfolk parakeet.
[src:bird/bird-p02] Human activities have allowed the expansion of a few temperate area species, such as the barn swallow and European starling.
[src:bird/bird-p02] In the tropics and sub-tropics, relatively more species are expanding due to human activities, particularly due to the spread of crops such as rice whose expansion in south Asia has benefitted at least 64 bird species, though may have harmed many more species.
